The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, April 13: Steel Authority of India Ltd (SAIL) today announced that it had become virtually a zero debt company. The steel major is also hopeful of posting a turnover in excess of Rs 30,000 crore for 2004-05. ?We have come this far on the strength of our sustained efforts to improve internal efficiencies supported by the buoyancy in the market,? SAIL chairman V. S. Jain said. While SAIL?s market borrowing last year stood at Rs 5,800 crore, its short-term deposits of similar magnitude had attained a zero status. The outstanding long-term dues could not be dissolved since they have been raised for longer terms, SAIL said in a statement.

 New Delhi, April 13: The International Monetary Fund (IMF) today asked India to improve its policy environment to stimulate private investment, including foreign direct investment. ?India has scope to increase its share in FDI from the current level of 5 per cent of the GDP,? said Andrew Berg, chief of development issues at IMF.

 Mumbai, April 13: All major stock exchanges, forex and money markets will remain closed tomorrow on account of Ambedkar Jayanti.

 New Delhi, April 13: Defence minister Pranab Mukherjee, heading the group of ministers on issues relating to the National Coal Wage Act, today said the Centre will take ?an appropriate? view on the issue. 




